        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="723" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d723">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>At 10:12 a.m. Korean time on July 27, Generals <persName corresp="#p_HMGWKJ1"
                        >Harrison</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_NILG1">Nam Il</persName>
                    finished signing the armistice documents at a building especially constructed at
                    Panmunjom for the ceremony. They did not exchange words. Later that afternoon at
                    Munsan-ni, <persName corresp="#p_CGMW1">General Clark</persName>, with his top
                    military advisers and a representative of the Republic of Korea Army in
                    attendance, countersigned the document. For 12 hours after the signature <pb
                        facs="0326" n="1444" xml:id="pg_1444"/> at Panmunjom, artillery and mortar
                    fire continued at the front, United Nations Command planes attacked North Korean
                    targets, and the United States Navy continued its offshore shelling of the North
                    Korean coast. Then, at 10 p.m. the fighting stopped and the armistice began. For
                    accounts of the signing ceremonies and other events on that last day, see
                    Hermes, <hi rend="italic">Truce Tent and Fighting Front</hi>, pages 489–491, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_CGMW1">Clark</persName>, <hi rend="italic">From the
                        Danube to the Yalu</hi>, pages 295–296. Because of the time difference
                    between Korea and Washington, President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> delivered a television and radio address to the
                    nation at 10 p.m. on July 26, announcing the signature of the armistice. For a
                    text of that statement and a similar one by Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>, see Department of State <hi
                        rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, August 3, 1953, pages 131–132. Also included in
                    that Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi> is a text of the
                    Armistice Agreement and the Supplementary Agreement on Prisoners of War, pages
                    132–140.</p>
            </div>
